"Van Doorslaer W., Stoks R., Duvivier C., Bednarska A., De Meester L.","Population dynamics determine genetic adaptation to temperature in daphnia",2009,"Evolution","63","7",,"1867","1878",,,10.1111/j.1558-5646.2009.00679.x,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-67649450101&partnerID=40&md5=1c7250218ee3b2f057d80e41ebbbd327","Laboratory of Aquatic Ecology and Evolutionary Biology, Katholieke Universiteit Leuven, Charles Deberiotstraat 32, B-3000 Leuven, Belgium; Department of Hydrobiology, University of Warsaw, Banacha 2, 02-097 Warszawa, Poland","Van Doorslaer, W., Laboratory of Aquatic Ecology and Evolutionary Biology, Katholieke Universiteit Leuven, Charles Deberiotstraat 32, B-3000 Leuven, Belgium; Stoks, R., Laboratory of Aquatic Ecology and Evolutionary Biology, Katholieke Universiteit Leuven, Charles Deberiotstraat 32, B-3000 Leuven, Belgium; Duvivier, C., Laboratory of Aquatic Ecology and Evolutionary Biology, Katholieke Universiteit Leuven, Charles Deberiotstraat 32, B-3000 Leuven, Belgium; Bednarska, A., Department of Hydrobiology, University of Warsaw, Banacha 2, 02-097 Warszawa, Poland; De Meester, L., Laboratory of Aquatic Ecology and Evolutionary Biology, Katholieke Universiteit Leuven, Charles Deberiotstraat 32, B-3000 Leuven, Belgium","Rising temperatures associated with global warming present a challenge to the fate of many aquatic organisms. Although rapid evolutionary response to temperature-mediated selection may allow local persistence of populations under global warming, and therefore is a key aspect of evolutionary biology, solid proof of its occurrence is rare. In this study, we tested for genetic adaptation to an increase in temperature in the water flea Daphnia magna, a keystone species in freshwater systems, by performing a thermal selection experiment under laboratory conditions followed by the quantification of microevolutionary responses to temperature for both life-history traits as well as for intraspecific competitive strength. After three months of selection, we found a microevolutionary response to temperature in performance, but only in one of two culling regimes, highlighting the importance of population dynamics in driving microevolutionary change within populations. Furthermore, there was an evolutionary increase in thermal plasticity in performance. The results of the competition experiment were in agreement with predictions based on performance as quantified in the life table experiment and illustrate that microevolution within a short time frame has the ability to influence the outcome of intraspecific competition. © 2009 The Society for the Study of Evolution.","Competition; Experimental evolution; Life history; Microevolution; Phenotypic plasticity; Population dynamics; Thermal selection","adaptation; crustacean; evolutionary biology; global warming; high temperature; intraspecific competition; keystone species; life history trait; life table; persistence; phenotypic plasticity; population dynamics; selection; temperature effect; temperature tolerance; acclimatization; animal; article; Daphnia; evolution; genetic selection; genetics; genotype; greenhouse effect; physiology; population dynamics; Acclimatization; Animals; Daphnia; Evolution; Genotype; Greenhouse Effect; Population Dynamics; Selection (Genetics); Cladocera; Daphnia; Daphnia magna; Siphonaptera (fleas)",,,,,,"Bennett, A.F., Dao, K.M., Lenski, R.E., Rapid evolution in response to high-temperature selection (1990) Nature, 346, pp. 79-81. , and; Bennett, A.F., Lenski, R.E., Mittler, J.E., Evolutionary adaptation to temperature. i Fitness responses of Escherichia coli to changes in its thermal environment (1992) Evolution, 46, pp. 16-30. , and; Bradshaw, W.E., Holzapfel, C.M., Evolutionary response to rapid climate change (2006) Science, 312 (5779), pp. 1477-1478. , DOI 10.1126/science.1127000; Brendonck, L., De Meester, L., Egg banks in freshwater zooplankton: Evolutionary and ecological archives in the sediment